static_createStyle.description:
Factory function that creates (or retrieves) a stylesheet with the given <code>id</code> in the head of the document and returns a function to create/modify style rules in that stylesheet.

See also <div data-action="jump2Nav" data-jumpkey="static_setStyle" class="linkLike">the setStyle documentation</div>.

<example>
const setMyStyling = $.createStyle(`mystyle`);
setMyStyling(`body {margin: 2rem; font: normal 12px/15px verdana, arial;}`);
</example>

static_removeCssRule.description:
Remove one or several css rule(s) (e.g. <code>.someclass:after</code>) from the custom JQL stylesheet (<code>&lt;style id="JQLStylesheet"></code>).

<example>
const yn = item => item === undefined ? `Yep` : `Nope`;
const div1 = $.virtual(`<div id="div1">I am div#div1</div>`);
const div2 = $.virtual(`<div id="div2">I am div#div2</div>`);
$.editCssRules(
  `#div1 {margin: 0.3rem; color: green; background-color: #EEE; }`,
  `#div2 {margin: 0.3rem; color: red; background-color: #EEE; }` );
popup.show( {
  content: $.virtual(`<div>`).append(div1, div2),
  callback: () => {
    $.removeCssRule(`#div1`, `#div2`);
    const rulesExist = [...$.node(`#JQLStylesheet`, document.documentElement).sheet.cssRules]
      .filter(r => r.cssText.startsWith(`#div1`) || r.cssText.startsWith(`#div1`))
   popup.show( {
     content: `Rules removed, so we expect <code>rulesExist?.cssText</code> to be undefined. Is that so? ${yn(rulesExist?.cssText)}`,
     closeAfter: 5,
   }); 
} );
</example>
<button class="exRunBttn" data-action="removeCssRulesEx">Try it</button>

static_editCssRule.description:
Formerly known as <div class="linkLike" div data-action="jump2Nav" data-jumpkey="static_setStyle">setStyle</div>.

On importing, JQL creates a custom stylesheet in the header (<code>&lt;style id="JQLStylesheet"></code>. Within this stylesheet you can create, remove and/or modify style rules using <code>[jql].editCssRule</code> 

You can use either real style rule string, or a selector and an Object defining the properties of that selector.

When a rule is valid and doesn't exist, it will be created. Existing rules are modified with the given parameters.

You can remove rule properties (e.g. <code>color</code>) or complete rules.
<ul>
<li>To remove one or more <i>rule properties</i>, use (for example) <code>$.editCssRule(`#someDiv`, {removeProperties: {color: 1, border: 1}})</code></li>
<li>To completely remove a css rule, use (for example) <code>$.editCssRule(`#someDiv`, {removeRule: 1})</code> <i>OR</i> use  <div class="linkLike" div data-action="jump2Nav" data-jumpkey="static_removeCssRule">removeCssRule</div></li></ul>
<example>
// a rule string
$.editCssRule(`#div1 {margin: 0.3rem; color: green; background-color: #EEE; }`);
// an object
$.editCssRule(`#div2`, {margin: "0.3rem", color: "red", backgroundColor: "#EEE"});
// -----------------------------------------------------^ Note: camelcased
const div1 = $.virtual(`<div id="div1">I am div#div1</div>`, /*[root element]*/);
const div2 = $.virtual(`<div id="div2">I am div#div2</div>`, /*[root element]*/);
popup.show( {
  content: $.virtual(`<div>`).append(div1, div2),
  callback: () => $.removeCssRule(`#div1`, `#div2`) } );
</example>
<button class="exRunBttn" data-action="editCssRuleEx">Try it</button>

instance_data.description:
Delivers a utility Object to manipulate data-attributes of the first element of the JQL instance collection.

<b>Notes</b>: 
<ul>
<li><code>[JQL instance].data</code> is a <i>static property</i>;</li>
<li><code>[JQL instance].data</code>'s methods are applied to the first element of the JQL instance collection;</li>
<li>The handling of casing for data-attributes is a bit weird and poorly documented imho. 
In html and css a data-attribute like <code>helloWorld</code> will show up as <code>hello-world</code>, for setting of/retrieval from the <code>dataset</code> it should be <code>helloWorld</code>. The methods of <code>[JQL instance].data</code> mitigate this (in other words: you can always use either <i>camelCased</i> or <i>dashed notation</i> data-attributes here). The example should demonstrate this;</li>
<li>The methods <code>.add</code> and <code>.remove</code> return the JQL instance (so, you can chain from them).
</ul>

The available methods:
<ul>
<li><code>all</code>: Retrieves all data-attribute values (e.g. <code>[JQL instance].data.all.someattribute</code>);</li>
<li><code>get(key: string[, whenUndefined: any])</code> Retrieves the value of data-attribute with [key] (e.g. <code>[JQL instance].data.get("someattribute")</code>. 
<code>whenUndefined</code> (optional) will be returned when the data-attribute does not exist);</li>
<li><code>add({key1: value1, ..., keyn: valuen})</code> Sets one or more attribute values (e.g. <code>[JQL instance].data.set({someattribute: "1"})</code>);</li>
<li><code>remove(key: string)</code> Removes the data-attribute with [key] (e.g. <code>[JQL instance].data.remove("someattribute")</code>).</li></ul>
<b>See also</b> <div class="linkLike" data-action="jump2Nav" data-jumpkey="instance_getData">getData</div> and <div class="linkLike" data-action="jump2Nav" data-jumpkey="instance_setData">setData</div>.

<example>
const helloWrld = $(`<div>Hello World again</div>`);
$.editCssRule(`[data-is-universe]:after {content: ' ... and the universe!'; color: red;}`);
helloWrld.data.add({isUniverse: true, something: "else", "dashed-prop-given": 1});
popup.show( {
  content: `<code>helloWrld.data.all</code> =&gt; ${JSON.stringify(helloWrld.data.all)}
            <br><code>helloWrld.data.get("something")</code> =&gt; ${helloWrld.data.get(`something`)}
            <br><code>helloWrld.data.all.isUniverse</code> =&gt; ${helloWrld.data.all.isUniverse}
            <br><code>helloWrld.data.all["is-universe]</code> =&gt; ${helloWrld.data.all["is-universe"]}
            <br><code>helloWrld.data.get("is-universe")</code> =&gt; ${helloWrld.data.get(`is-universe`)}
            <br><code>helloWrld.data.get("isUniverse")</code> =&gt; ${helloWrld.data.get(`isUniverse`)}
            <br><code>helloWrld.data.get("dashed-prop-given")</code> =&gt; ${helloWrld.data.get(`dashed-prop-given`)}
            <br><code>helloWrld.data.all.nonexisting</code> =&gt; ${helloWrld.data.all.nonexisting}
            <br><code>helloWrld.data.get("nonexisting", "no sir, I'm not here")</code> =&gt; ${
              helloWrld.data.get("nonexisting", "no sir, I'm not here")}`,
  callback: () => helloWrld.data.remove("isUniverse"), // note: may also be .remove("is-universe")
} );
</example>
