instance_Style.description:
Delivers a utility object to manipulate styling of a JQL instance (element collection) or retrieve computed style value(s) from the first element of the element collection.

The available methods:
<ul>
<li><code>inline(rules:Object&lt;string, string>)</code> set the styling of all elements of the JQL instance collection using the style attribute (<code>style="..."</code>)</li>
<li><code>inSheet(rules::Object&lt;string, string>)</code> set the styling of all elements of the JQL instance collection using the JQL custom stylesheet. When rules contains a <code>className</code> property, the className and the rules values will be added to the styleSheet, otherwise a intermediate className will be created for the given rules (see the example)</li>
<li><code>byRule({classes2Apply: Array&lt;string>, rules: Array&lt;string>})</code> Add one or more rules to the JQL custom stylesheet and (optionally) apply one or more classes to the concerning JQL Instance. See second example.</li>
<li><code>computed</code> (getter) Retrieves the complete computedStyle of the first element of the JQL instance collection.</li>
<li><code>valueOf(key:string)</code> Retrieve the computed value of a style property (see example)</li>
</ul>
<b>Notes</b>:

<ul><li><code>inline</code>, <code>inSheet</code> and <code>byRule</code> return the JQL instance.</li>
<li>For the [key] value of <code>valueOf</code> you can either supply camel cased or dashed notation (e.g. "borderLeft" vs "border-left")</li></ul>

<example>
// inline
const hello1 = $.virtual(`<p data-id="tmpEx"></p>`).Style
  .inline({ paddingLeft: `4px`, color: `white`, backgroundColor: `#000` });
const hello1Html = `HTML of hello1: ${hello1.HTML.get(true, true)}`;
hello1.append(`<div>${hello1Html}</div>`);

// inSheet with given className
const hello2 = $.virtual(`<p data-id="tmpEx" class="leftRedBorder"></p>`).Style
  .inSheet({className: `leftRedBorder`, paddingLeft: `4px`, color: `green`, borderLeft: `12px solid red`});
const hello2Html = `HTML of hello2: ${hello2.HTML.get(true, true)}`;
hello2.append(`<div>${hello2Html}</div>`);

// inSheet, className generated
const hello3 = $.virtual(`<p data-id="tmpEx"></p>`).Style
  .inSheet({paddingLeft: `4px`, color: `green`, borderLeft: `12px solid green`});
const hello3Html = `HTML of hello3: ${hello3.HTML.get(true, true)}`;
hello3.append(`<div>${hello3Html}</div>`);
const hello3GeneratedClassName = [...hello3[0]?.classList]?.shift();

// computed (note: randomNr is a utility function)
const computedHello3 = $(`<div>`)
  .html(`<code>hello3.Style.valueOf("borderLeftColor")</code>: ${
    hello3.toDOM().Style.valueOf(`borderLeftColor`)}.<br>&nbsp;<b>⤷</b> Equivalent
    <code>hello3.Style.computed.borderLeftColor</code>: ${
      hello3.Style.computed.borderLeftColor}`);
const computed = hello3.Style.computed;
const sliceStart = randomNr(computed.length, 10) - 10;
const hello3Computed = `<div><br><code>hello3.Style.computed</code> 
  (10 of ${computed.length} rules, random sample)<ul>${
  [...computed]
  .slice( sliceStart, sliceStart + 10)
  .map( (v) => `<li>${v}: ${computed[v]}</li>`)
  .join(``) }</ul></div>`.replace(/\n+\s{2,}/g, ` `);

popup.show({
  content: $(`<div>`).append(hello1, hello2, hello3, computedHello3, hello3Computed,),
  callback: () => $.removeCssRule(`.${hello3GeneratedClassName}`, `.leftRedBorder`) } );
</example>
<button class="exRunBttn" data-action="styleObjInStyleEx">Try it</button>
<example>
const helloElem = $.virtual(`<div>Hello <span>World</span></div>`);
helloElem.Style.byRule( {
  classes2Apply: [`test1`],
  // Notes: 
  // - the style rules are exactly what you would put in a css-file/style element
  // - you can add many rules here. Only [classes2Apply] will be relevant for the element at hand (here [helloElem])
  rules: [ 
    `.test1 { backgroundColor: #EEE; color: green }`,
    `.test2 { color: red; }`,
    `#test3 { color: blue; }`,] } );
helloElem.find$(`span`)?.addClass(`test2`);
popup.show({
  content: $(`<div>This resulted in:</div>`).attr({id: `test3`}).append(helloElem),
  callback: () => $.removeCssRule(`.test1`, `.test2`, `#test3`) });
</example>
<button class="exRunBttn" data-action="styleRulingsEx">Try it</button>

static_fn.description:
Add custom method to JQL instances. 

The first argument of function [fn] is the JQL instance. Calling the added method, you only need [...arguments]. See both examples for usage.

<example>
// we use the instance itself to set the title property
$.fn(`addTitle`, (me, ttl) => ttl ? me.prop(`title`, ttl) : me);
const someDiv = $.virtual(`<div data-id="tmpEx">Hello world</div>`);
popup.show( {
  content: someDiv
            .addTitle("hi there!")
            .append(`<div>My title is now "${someDiv.prop(`title`)}". Hover me!</div>`),
  callback: someDiv.remove(),
});
</example>
<button class="exRunBttn" data-action="fnEx">Try it</button>
<example>
// we use the first element of the instance to colorize. Return [me] to not break the chain.
$.fn( `colorRed`, me => { me[0].style.color = "red"; return me; } );
const someDiv = $.virtual(`<div data-id="tmpEx">Hello world</div>`);
popup.show( {
  content: someDiv.append($(`<div>There we have it</div>`).colorRed()),
  callback: someDiv.remove(),
});
</example>
